'''Matheus Santos Carneiro da Cunha''' (Brazilian Portuguese: [[Help:IPA/Portuguese|[maˈtews ˈkũ.ɲɐ]]], born 27 May 1999) is a Brazilian professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]], [[attacking midfielder]], or [[winger (association football)|winger]] for {{English football updater|ManchesU}} club [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] and the [[Brazil national football team|Brazil national team]].

Cunha played youth football in Brazil for [[Coritiba Foot Ball Club|Coritiba]]. At the age of 18, he moved to Europe to join Swiss club [[FC Sion|Sion]]. He then played for [[Bundesliga]] clubs [[RB Leipzig]] and [[Hertha BSC]], before joining [[Atlético Madrid]] in August 2021. In January 2023, he moved to [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]], initially on loan. In August 2025, he completed a move to Manchester United on a five-year deal worth £62.5 million from Wolverhampton Wanderers.

Cunha won a gold medal with the [[Brazil national under-23 football team|Brazil under-23]] team at the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Summer Olympics]]. He made his senior international debut in September 2021.

==Early life==
Cunha was born in the city of [[João Pessoa, Paraíba|João Pessoa]], Brazil.<ref name="sion"/> He originally played [[futsal]] for a club in [[Recife]], before switching to football.<ref name="puskasaward">{{cite news|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/programas/esporte-espetacular/noticia/indicado-ao-puskas-matheus-cunha-faz-sua-campanha-estou-chamando-o-brasil-inteiro-pra-votar.ghtml |title=Indicado ao Puskas, Matheus Cunha faz sua campanha: "Estou chamando o Brasil inteiro pra votar" |website=globoesporte.globo.com |date=25 August 2019 |access-date=16 August 2022}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Sion===
Cunha played youth football for [[Coritiba Foot Ball Club|Coritiba]], before joining Swiss club [[FC Sion|Sion]] at the age of 18 in July 2017, after impressing scouts at the [[Dallas Cup]] youth tournament.<ref name="sion">{{cite news|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/pb/futebol/noticia/aos-18-anos-paraibano-vira-sensacao-do-futebol-suico-apos-se-destacar-pelo-coxa.ghtml |title=Aos 18 anos, paraibano vira sensação do futebol suíço após se destacar pelo Coxa |website=globoesporte.globo.com |date=10 November 2017 |access-date=16 August 2022}}</ref> In May 2018, he scored a hat-trick in a 4–1 victory over [[FC Thun|Thun]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://globoesporte.globo.com/futebol/futebol-internacional/noticia/aos-18-anos-matheus-cunha-e-o-artilheiro-brasileiro-na-suica.ghtml |title=Aos 18 anos, Matheus Cunha é o artilheiro brasileiro na Suíça |website=globoesporte.globo.com |date=22 May 2018 |access-date=16 August 2022}}</ref>

===RB Leipzig===
[[File:Matheus Cunha (cropped) 20180920 Fussball, UEFA Europa League, RB Leipzig - FC Salzburg by Stepro StP 7968 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|180px|Cunha with [[RB Leipzig]] in 2018]]
On 24 June 2018, Cunha joined [[Bundesliga]] club [[RB Leipzig]] on a five-year deal.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/matheus-cunha-rb-leipzig-not-as-quick-as-timo-werner-509880.jsp |title=RB Leipzig's Samba speedster Matheus Cunha hot on the trail of Timo Werner |publisher=Bundesliga |date=2018 |access-date=16 August 2022 |archive-date=7 May 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210507103513/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/matheus-cunha-rb-leipzig-not-as-quick-as-timo-werner-509880.jsp |url-status=dead }}</ref> He scored his maiden Bundesliga goal against his future club [[Hertha BSC]], to mark a 3–0 win in November 2018.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/hertha-berlin-rb-leipzig-live-line-ups-stats-timo-werner-salomon-kalou-poulsen-fantasy-516131.jsp |title=Timo Werner scores twice as RB Leipzig see off Hertha Berlin in the capital |website=bundesliga.com |date=2018 |access-date=16 August 2022 |archive-date=6 June 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200606033403/https://www.bundesliga.com/en/news/Bundesliga/hertha-berlin-rb-leipzig-live-line-ups-stats-timo-werner-salomon-kalou-poulsen-fantasy-516131.jsp |url-status=dead }}</ref> He scored a goal against [[Bayer 04 Leverkusen|Bayer Leverkusen]] in April 2019 that won the Bundesliga Goal of the Month award,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bundesliga.com/en/bundesliga/news/goal-of-the-month-2018-19-bayern-munich-borussia-dortmund-schalke-rb-leipzig-2747-1210 |title=Bayern Munich's Franck Ribery wins Goal of the Month for May |website=bundesliga.com |date=2019 |access-date=16 August 2022}}</ref> and was nominated for the [[FIFA Puskás Award]].<ref name="puskasaward"/> He finished the [[2018–19 UEFA Europa League]] season with 6 goals.

===Hertha BSC===
On 31 January 2020, having played 10 games mostly as a substitute and scored once for RB Leipzig in the first half of the season, Cunha moved to fellow Bundesliga team [[Hertha BSC]] on an undisclosed "long-term" contract.<ref>{{cite magazine |title=Hertha Berlin Signs Matheus Cunha, Continues Spending Spree |url=https://www.si.com/soccer/2020/01/31/matheus-cunha-transfer-hertha-berlin-rb-leipzig |access-date=15 December 2024 |magazine=Sports Illustrated |agency=Associated Press |date=31 January 2020}}</ref>

===Atlético Madrid===
On 25 August 2021, Cunha joined [[Atlético Madrid]] on a five-year deal for an estimated fee of €30&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hernández |first1=Carlos |title=Official: Atletico Madrid sign Matheus Cunha |url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/atletico-madrid/2021/08/25/61262a4722601d65188b457c.html |access-date=15 December 2024 |work=Marca |date=25 August 2021}}</ref> He scored his first goal against [[Levante UD|Levante]] to seal a 2–2 draw.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eurosport.com/football/liga/2021-2022/levante-v-atletico-madrid-follow-live_sto8602110/story.shtml|title=LEVANTE 2–2 ATLETICO MADRID: TWO ENIS BARDHI PENALTIES DENY LA LIGA CHAMPIONS AS DIEGO SIMEONE SEES RED|work=Eurosport|date=29 October 2021|access-date=25 February 2023|last=Cummins|first=Jo}}</ref>

===Wolverhampton Wanderers===
[[File:Matheus Cunha (cropped) Wolves vs West Ham United Full Time.jpg|thumb|upright|Cunha with [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] in 2023]]
On 1 January 2023, Cunha joined [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] on loan for the remainder of the 2022–23 season,<ref>{{cite web |title=Cunha becomes Lopetegui's first signing |url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/mens-first-team/20221224-cunha-becomes-lopeteguis-first-signing/ |website=Wolverhampton Wanderers |access-date=25 December 2022 |date=25 December 2022 }}</ref> in a deal which stipulated the move would become permanent in the summer of 2023, certain clauses in the loan agreement having been met.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64093737|title=Wolves sign Matheus Cunha on an initial loan from Atletico Madrid|work=BBC Sport|date=26 December 2022|access-date=27 December 2022}}</ref> Cunha's first appearance was as a second-half substitute in a 1–1 draw away to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] on 4 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64106275|title=Aston Villa 1–1 Wolverhampton Wanderers: Danny Ings denies Wolves in West Midlands derby|first=Harry|last=Poole|work=BBC Sport|date=4 January 2023|access-date=1 January 2024}}</ref> His first goal for Wolves came in a 4–2 defeat at home to [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]] on 18 March.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64923722|title=Wolverhampton Wanderers 2–4 Leeds United: Rare away win lifts visitors out of bottom three|first=Matthew|last=Howarth|work=BBC Sport|date=18 March 2023|access-date=1 January 2024}}</ref>

Cunha's first goal of the [[2023–24 Premier League|2023–24 Premier League season]] came in a 3–2 defeat away to [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on 3 September 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66631568|title=Crystal Palace 3–2 Wolverhampton Wanderers: Odsonne Edouard scores twice as Palace beat Wolves|first=Marissa|last=Thomas|work=BBC Sport|date=3 September 2023|access-date=1 January 2024}}</ref> He scored his first [[FA Cup]] goal, a penalty, in extra-time of a 3–2 Third Round replay victory over [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] at Molineux on 16 January 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/67984477|title=Wolverhampton Wanderers 3–2 Brentford: Wolves set up FA Cup tie with West Brom|first=Simon|last=Stone|work=BBC Sport|date=16 January 2024}}</ref> He scored again in the next round against [[Black Country derby|Wolves' bitterest rivals]], [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]], in a 2–0 victory at [[The Hawthorns]] on 28 January, a goal that led to crowd unrest breaking out in sections of the ground designated for West Brom supporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68110807|title=West Brom 0–2 Wolves: Visitors progress after crowd trouble sees game suspended|website=BBC Sport|first=Simon|last=Stone|date=28 January 2024}}</ref> On 4 February, he scored his first Wolves [[hat-trick]] in a 4–2 away victory against [[Chelsea FC|Chelsea]], becoming just the second Wolves player ([[List of Premier League hat-tricks|after Diogo Jota in January 2019]]) to score a hat-trick in the Premier League and only the fourth opposition player to score a hat-trick at [[Stamford Bridge (stadium)|Stamford Bridge]] in Premier League history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/68120824|title=Chelsea 2–4 Wolverhampton Wanderers: Matheus Cunha hat-trick as Wolves stun Blues|last=Poole|first=Harry|website=BBC Sport|date=4 February 2024|access-date=9 February 2024}}</ref> He scored 14 goals over the season.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bate |first1=Adam |title=Matheus Cunha interview: Wolves forward on refinding his passion for football after clicking with Gary O'Neil |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11699/13140353/matheus-cunha-interview-wolves-forward-on-refinding-his-passion-for-football-after-clicking-with-gary-oneil |access-date=15 December 2024 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=27 May 2024}}</ref>

Cunha scored his first goal of the [[2024–25 Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C. season|2024–25 season]] in a 6–2 home defeat to Chelsea.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cgjvyxxqj11t |title=Wolves 2–6 Chelsea: Noni Madueke's hat-trick gives Enzo Maresca first Premier League win }}</ref> Cunha also scored in defeats to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] and [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] before he scored a late equaliser against [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] to give Wolves their second point of the season.

Cunha then scored Wolves' second goal in a 2–0 win over [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]] which was the team's first win of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/ckgv3vgl4zzt?page=6|title=Wolves 2–0 Southampton: Pablo Sarabia & Matheus Cunha lift Wolves off bottom of Premier League|publisher=BBC Sport|first=Nick|last=Mashiter|date=9 November 2024|access-date=11 November 2024}}</ref> Two weeks later Cunha scored a brace in a 4–1 win over [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] to lift the team out of the relegation zone.<ref>{{cite web |last=Tobin |first=Sam |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/cunhas-sublime-double-gives-wolves-4-1-comeback-win-fulham-2024-11-23/ |title=Cunha's sublime double gives Wolves 4–1 comeback win at Fulham |publisher=Reuters |date=23 November 2024 }}</ref>

On 14 December, in a 2–1 home loss to [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]] in the last game before [[Gary O'Neil]]'s dismissal, Cunha appeared to elbow an employee of the visiting club in the back of the head, before reaching to the same man's face and pulling his glasses off.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Madeley |first1=Steve |title=Cunha's steward clash, Ait-Nouri's anger – breaking down Wolves' latest moments of madness |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5994406/2024/12/15/wolves-ipswich-cunha-ait-nouri/ |access-date=15 December 2024 |work=The Athletic |date=15 December 2024}}</ref> Cunha was charged with misconduct by [[the Football Association]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Wolves striker Cunha charged with misconduct by FA |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cjdnyx4e210o |access-date=21 December 2024 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 December 2024}}</ref> On 31 December, Cunha was given a two game ban from the FA with a fine of £80,000 following the incident.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mashiter |first1=Nick |title=Matheus Cunha: Wolverhampton Wanderers striker banned for two games |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/ce8xj6dm2rro |work=BBC Sport |date=31 December 2024}}</ref> On 1 February 2025, he extended his contract with the club until 2029 shortly after he scored in Wolves' 2–0 victory over [[Aston Villa F.C|Aston Villa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wolves.co.uk/news/mens-first-team/20250201-cunha-pens-new-wolves-deal/ |title=Cunha pens new Wolves deal |publisher=Wolverhampton Wanderers FC |date=1 February 2025 }}</ref> Cunha finished the 2024–25 season with 15 league goals, marking a personal best and ranking as his club's highest scorer.<ref>{{cite web |last=Furniss |first=Matt |url=https://theanalyst.com/articles/matheus-cunha-man-utd-wolves-transfer |title=Matheus Cunha Proved Himself as Wolves' Most Influential Player – His Expected Move to Man Utd Would Be Deserved |publisher=Opta Analyst |date=28 May 2025 }}</ref>

===Manchester United===
On 1 June 2025, fellow Premier League club [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] announced an agreement with Wolves for the transfer of Cunha.<ref>{{cite news |date=1 June 2025 |title=Man Utd agrees to sign Matheus Cunha from Wolves |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/man-utd-agrees-to-sign-matheus-cunha-from-wolves |access-date=1 June 2025 |publisher=[[Manchester United F.C.]]}}</ref> On 12 June 2025, United completed the transfer for a reported fee of £62.5m.<ref>{{cite news |date=12 June 2025 |title=OFFICIAL: Matheus Cunha signs for Manchester United |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/matheus-cunha-signs-for-man-utd-from-wolves |access-date=12 June 2025 |publisher=[[Manchester United F.C.]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=12 June 2025 |title=Cunha completes 'dream' £62.5m Man Utd move |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/c0r1lx8vg7jo |publisher=BBC Sport}}</ref> On 17 August, he made his debut for the club in a 1–0 loss against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in the league.<ref>{{Cite web |date=17 August 2025 |title=Calafiori strikes after goalkeeper's error as Arsenal grind to win at Manchester United |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2025/aug/17/manchester-united-arsenal-premier-league-match-report |access-date=23 August 2025 }}</ref>

On 27 August 2025, during the second round of the [[EFL Cup]] against [[EFL League Two|League Two]] side Grimsby Town, Cunha missed the winning penalty during a penalty shootout, which would have sent United into the third round of the EFL Cup, but after fellow new United signing [[Bryan Mbeumo]] also missed his penalty, United lost.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Stone |first=Simon |title=Grimsby 2–2 Manchester United (12–11 pens): Bryan Mbeumo misses in shootout as Man Utd humiliated |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c5y387ngzz4t |access-date=30 August 2025 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> Later that year, on 25 October, he netted his first goal for the club in a 4–2 win over Brighton scoring from outside the box with a low shot.<ref>{{cite web |last=Hunter |first=Laura |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/man-utd-vs-brighton/report/531216 |title=Man Utd 4–2 Brighton: Matheus Cunha scores first goal as Ruben Amorim's side continue momentum with third straight Premier League win |publisher=Sky Sports |date=25 October 2025 }}</ref> On 25 January 2026, he scored the winning goal in a 3–2 away win over Arsenal, securing his club's first league win at the [[Emirates Stadium]] since December 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/story/_/id/47726339/beating-arsenal-puts-manchester-united-premier-league-title-race |title=Beating Arsenal puts Man United into Premier League title race |publisher=ESPN |date=25 January 2026 }}</ref>

==International career==
===Under-23 team===
With [[Brazil national under-23 football team|Brazil's under-23 team]], Cunha was the top scorer of the [[2019 Toulon Tournament]] and the [[2020 CONMEBOL Pre-Olympic Tournament]], winning the former and finishing as runner-up in the latter, thus securing qualification to the Olympics for the Brazil team with the latter performance. On 17 June 2021, he was named in Brazil's squad for the [[Football at the 2020 Summer Olympics – Men's tournament|2020 Summer Olympics]] in Tokyo.<ref>{{cite web |title=Seleção Olímpica é convocada para os Jogos Olímpicos de Tóquio 2020 |work=Confederação Brasileira de Futebol |url=https://www.cbf.com.br/selecao-brasileira/jogos/olimpicos-de-toquio-2020/selecao-olimpica-e-convocada-para-os-jogos-olimpicos-de-toquio |publisher=[[Brazilian Football Confederation|CBF]] |access-date=17 June 2021 |date=17 June 2021}}</ref> In August 2021, he won a gold medal with Brazil at the Olympics, having scored 3 goals in 5 appearances at the tournament.<ref name="goldmedal">{{cite news|url=https://www.marca.com/en/football/atletico-madrid/2021/08/25/61262a4722601d65188b457c.html |title=Official: Atletico Madrid sign Matheus Cunha |website=marca.com |date=25 August 2021 |access-date=16 August 2022}}</ref>

===Senior team===
In September 2020, Cunha was called up to the senior [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] squad for [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] matches against [[Bolivia national football team|Bolivia]] and [[Peru national football team|Peru]] on 9 and 13 October 2020, respectively.<ref name="cbf.com.br">{{cite web |title=Tite convoca a Seleção Brasileira para a estreia nas Eliminatórias |url=https://www.cbf.com.br/selecao-brasileira/noticias/selecao-masculina/tite-convoca-a-selecao-brasileira-para-a-estreia-nas-eliminatorias |publisher=[[Brazilian Football Confederation|CBF]] |access-date=18 September 2020 |date=18 September 2020 |language=pt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Matheus Cunha está convocado para a Seleção Brasileira |url=https://www.cbf.com.br/selecao-brasileira/noticias/selecao-masculina/matheus-cunha-esta-convocado-para-a-selecao-brasileira|publisher=[[Brazilian Football Confederation]] |access-date=25 September 2020 |date=25 September 2020 |language=pt}}</ref>

Cunha made his debut for the [[Brazil national football team|senior national team]] on 2 September 2021, in a [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|World Cup qualifier]] against [[Chile national football team|Chile]], a 1–0 away victory. He substituted [[Gabriel Barbosa]] in the 78th minute.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[FIFA]]|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/worldcup/qatar2022/qualifiers/conmebol/match-center/400104588|title=Chile v Brazil game report|date=2 September 2021}}</ref>

He scored his first international goal for Brazil on 25 March 2025, in a 4–1 away defeat to [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Argentina 4–1 Brazil: World Cup holders qualify for 2026 tournament after inflicting rivals' heaviest qualifying loss |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/argentina-vs-brazil/report/495407 |access-date=19 April 2025 |website=Sky Sports |language=en}}</ref>

==Style of play==
Cunha is a highly versatile, creative forward known for gifted ball-carrying, intelligent movement, and clinical long-range shooting. His primary strengths lie in transitioning play, [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling]] in tight spaces, and delivering both goals and [[Assist (association football)|assists]]. He is effective as a [[Forward (association football)#Centre-forward|central striker]], [[attacking midfielder]], or [[inside forward]].<ref name="AthleticCunha">{{cite web |title=How could Matheus Cunha and Bryan Mbeumo fit into Ruben Amorim's system? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6413130/2025/06/09/cunha-mbeumo-manchester-united-amorim-premier-league/ |website=The Athletic (via The New York Times) |date=9 June 2025 |access-date=7 August 2025}}</ref><ref name="PL2025">{{cite web |last=Keble |first=Alex |title=Why Cunha is a perfect fit for Amorim's Man Utd |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/4321863 |website=Premier League |date=27 May 2025 |access-date=7 August 2025}}</ref><ref name="SkyMaverick">{{cite web |last=Bate |first=Adam |title=Matheus Cunha to Man Utd: Wolves forward is an emotional maverick, not a robot, but he could light up Old Trafford |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/13353754/matheus-cunha-to-man-utd-wolves-forward-is-an-emotional-maverick-not-a-robot-but-he-could-light-up-old-trafford |website=Sky Sports |date=2 June 2025 |access-date=7 August 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Johnston |first=Neil |title=Why does Cunha want Man Utd move and where does he fit? |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cn4gjy3wxr3o |work=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2025 |access-date=10 August 2025}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/news/4294600 |title=Analysis: Why Cunha is Wolves' leader of the pack |publisher=Premier League |date=22 April 2025 |access-date=20 March 2026 |language=en}}</ref>

However, his playing style is also noted for being highly instinctive and emotional, sometimes lacking tactical discipline. Cunha has described himself as a "maverick" who prefers freedom over structure. Despite not being known for his work rate, he has demonstrated impressive defensive ability, particularly in ball recoveries and interceptions.<ref name="SkyMaverick"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Who tops the 2024/25 Premier League running charts? |url=https://www.premierleague.com/en/news/4272290 |website=Premier League |publisher=Premier League |date=16 May 2025 |access-date=8 August 2025}}</ref>

==Career statistics==
